Git notes are invisible. GitHub doesn't render them. git log
doesn't show them unless activated. git diff ignores them. PRs don't
include them. CI doesn't see them. This is the feature, not a bug.

Mycelium must never impede normal git workflows. A developer who has
never heard of mycelium should be able to clone, commit, push, and
PR without ever encountering a mycelium note. Zero friction for
non-participants.

But the network is there. Agents read it on arrival, write to it on
departure, and use it to coordinate across sessions. When a human
wants to see the reasoning layer: git config --add notes.displayRef
refs/notes/mycelium — and suddenly git log shows everything.

The metaphor is literal: mycelium is the fungal network underground.
The mushrooms (visible artifacts: commits, PRs, code) are what
people see. The network that connects them is invisible until you
dig. Transparent, not private. Underground, not encrypted.

This constrains the tool: mycelium must never modify tracked files,
never add to .gitignore, never create visible artifacts in the
working tree. The only trace is refs/notes/mycelium in .git/ and
an optional .git/mycelium-branch file. Everything else is invisible.
